00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:52.210
AUDIENCE: What do a cellphone,
a river, and a cancer cell

00:05:52.210 --> 00:05:53.430
have in common?

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:55.530
The answer is fractals.

00:05:55.530 --> 00:05:58.410
Fractals in mathematics
are never ending patterns.

00:05:58.410 --> 00:06:01.080
Scientists can program
these infinite patterns

00:06:01.080 --> 00:06:03.470
by repeating a simple
mathematical process

00:06:03.470 --> 00:06:04.860
over and over.

00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:08.380
So if you zoom in, you'll see
the shape-- the same shape,

00:06:08.380 --> 00:06:10.670
again and again and again.

00:06:10.670 --> 00:06:13.210
And here I would
show an animation

00:06:13.210 --> 00:06:15.230
of that on a computer.

00:06:15.230 --> 00:06:18.290
Similarly, a tree grows
by repetitive branching.

00:06:18.290 --> 00:06:20.710
Just like a fractal, a
tree extends its branches

00:06:20.710 --> 00:06:23.500
one smaller than the
other, but similar.

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:25.950
A tree can't grow
as far and precisely

00:06:25.950 --> 00:06:29.200
as a truly mathematical fractal,
but we can still study nature

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:30.830
in terms of fractals.

00:06:30.830 --> 00:06:33.120
In fact, so many
things in nature

00:06:33.120 --> 00:06:36.420
have these pattern
properties-- and show animation

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:38.900
of all those
things-- it sometimes

00:06:38.900 --> 00:06:43.060
feels like the world itself
is one giant fractal.

00:06:43.060 --> 00:06:45.410
Rivers of the planet flow
like the blood vessels

00:06:45.410 --> 00:06:46.630
in our bodies.

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:50.160
Lightning bolts become
electrifying rivers of the sky.

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:54.140
And just look at this honey--
show fractal honey-- here's

00:06:54.140 --> 00:06:58.950
something even wackier, a
brain-fractal shaped forest.

00:06:58.950 --> 00:07:01.260
One way to explain this
abundance of patterns

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:04.040
is the fact that nature
is just great at reusing

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:05.520
efficient mechanisms.

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:08.820
How and why that happens,
we can't really tell.

00:07:08.820 --> 00:07:11.970
But although the existence of
fractals remains a mystery,

00:07:11.970 --> 00:07:15.280
mathematicians have found a way
to study the wacky structures.

00:07:15.280 --> 00:07:17.820
Clouds are not spheres
and bark is not smooth,

00:07:17.820 --> 00:07:22.050
but with fractal geometry we
can mathematically explore them.

00:07:22.050 --> 00:07:26.220
In the 1970s, a mathematician,
named Benoit Mandelbrot,

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:29.460
was hired to investigate
noise in telephone lines.

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:32.130
Now Mandelbrot loved
connecting images with numbers,

00:07:32.130 --> 00:07:34.740
so he immediately graphed
the data he collected.

00:07:34.740 --> 00:07:39.060
And he came up with this--
show Mandelbrot fractal,

00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:42.420
and also the equation
that comes along with it.

00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:44.680
At first, the image
didn't look too special.

00:07:44.680 --> 00:07:48.070
In fact, it kind of resembled
a turtle with a giant head.

00:07:48.070 --> 00:07:51.560
It wasn't until night time
that Mandelbrot looked closer.

00:07:51.560 --> 00:07:54.160
He zoomed in once and found
a smaller turtle etched

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:56.960
onto the original one,
and an even smaller turtle

00:07:56.960 --> 00:07:58.150
on that one.

00:07:58.150 --> 00:08:00.280
Mandelbrot kept
zooming and zooming

00:08:00.280 --> 00:08:02.610
and the turtles kept
shrinking and shrinking,

00:08:02.610 --> 00:08:05.340
but they were still
all the same shape.

00:08:05.340 --> 00:08:08.300
Mandelbrot was convinced
he'd seen a nightmare.

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:10.830
But when the shape remained
on the screen the next day,

00:08:10.830 --> 00:08:12.790
Mandelbrot knew he
was onto something

00:08:12.790 --> 00:08:16.490
huge, a simple equation
applied repeatedly,

00:08:16.490 --> 00:08:18.910
carried incredible properties.

00:08:18.910 --> 00:08:22.100
What if, thought he, you
could create such expressions

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:24.530
for other natural phenomena?

00:08:24.530 --> 00:08:27.210
And that's exactly what
mathematicians do today.

00:08:27.210 --> 00:08:31.550
Fractal geometry allows them
to model, say, mountain ranges,

00:08:31.550 --> 00:08:34.350
and then use the models to
study earthquakes or creed

00:08:34.350 --> 00:08:37.480
realistic special effects
for our favorite movies.

00:08:37.480 --> 00:08:39.289
So you would show
animating a mountain

00:08:39.289 --> 00:08:42.880
range from fractal triangles,
and then a scene from Star Wars

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:46.300
where that was used,
or other movie.

00:08:46.300 --> 00:08:47.990
In healthier news,
fractals may also

00:08:47.990 --> 00:08:51.190
help doctors diagnose cancer
faster and more accurately.

00:08:51.190 --> 00:08:53.090
They can study the
edges of various cells

00:08:53.090 --> 00:08:55.410
in our bodies using
fractal geometry.

00:08:55.410 --> 00:08:58.000
Here the cell on the right
is more jagged and repeating

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.030
than the one on the
left, which means

00:09:00.030 --> 00:09:03.110
it's the more aggressive,
faster-growing cancer cell.

00:09:03.110 --> 00:09:04.570
This way of
discovering cancer can

00:09:04.570 --> 00:09:08.480
be that 10 times more effective
than the current methods.

00:09:08.480 --> 00:09:11.430
So that's how cancer
cells and rivers relate.

00:09:11.430 --> 00:09:13.360
But what about cell phones?

00:09:13.360 --> 00:09:15.710
They aren't really
part of nature.

00:09:15.710 --> 00:09:18.050
Well, in the '90s
a radio astronomer

00:09:18.050 --> 00:09:20.290
by the name of Nathan
Cohen was having

00:09:20.290 --> 00:09:22.160
troubles with this landlord.

00:09:22.160 --> 00:09:25.210
The man wouldn't let him put
a radio antenna on the roof.

00:09:25.210 --> 00:09:28.490
So Cohen decided to make a
more compact fractal radio

00:09:28.490 --> 00:09:30.240
antenna instead.

00:09:30.240 --> 00:09:31.850
The landlord didn't notice it.

00:09:31.850 --> 00:09:34.400
And it worked better
than the ones before.

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:37.350
Working further, Cohen
designed a new version,

00:09:37.350 --> 00:09:40.550
this time using a shape
called the menger sponge.

00:09:40.550 --> 00:09:42.530
The fractal's
infinite sponginess

00:09:42.530 --> 00:09:46.100
allowed the antenna to receive
multiple different signals.

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:47.850
The menger sponge is
not really the sponge

00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:49.460
you'd be scrubbing
your back with,

00:09:49.460 --> 00:09:51.220
but you can still
think of it like that.

00:09:51.220 --> 00:09:54.490
Imagine both water and soap
getting through sponges holes,

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:57.800
except the water is wifi and
the soap is, say, Bluetooth.

00:09:57.800 --> 00:09:59.790
Without Cohen's
sponge, your cellphone

00:09:59.790 --> 00:10:01.830
would have to look
something like a giraffe

00:10:01.830 --> 00:10:03.800
to receive both those signals.

00:10:03.800 --> 00:10:06.130
Not quite as handy, is it?

00:10:06.130 --> 00:10:08.360
Fractals are
already very common,

00:10:08.360 --> 00:10:10.690
yet we're still searching
for more applications,

00:10:10.690 --> 00:10:13.150
asking questions,
building new patterns,

00:10:13.150 --> 00:10:16.810
and exploring nature's best,
here at MIT and everywhere

00:10:16.810 --> 00:10:18.010
in the world.

00:10:18.010 --> 00:10:19.010
Look around you.

